post_text: We welcome Ms. Kathleen Olmsted as the new Monte Vista Elementary School principal! She is new to the district, but not to Sonoma County, where she has spent her entire career. She most recently worked at Santa Rosa City Schools as a principal and then as the coordinator of state and federal programs. She’s also served as an assistant principal, special education coordinator and a speech and language therapist in districts in the county. Welcome Ms.Olmsted!

shared_text:
California Department of Education
June 15 at 3:16 PM ·

Students in the middle and high school age range are invited to attend "Student Support Circle: Institutional Racism and Implicit Bias" hosted by the CDE and State Superintendent Tony Thurmond, this Thursday, June 18 at 4 p.m, on Facebook Live. It's hosted in partnership with with National Equity Project, and will feature California Surgeon General Dr. Nadine Burke Harris.

It will also feature students from across the state speaking about what they've experienced and talk about practical solutions to institutional racism and implicit basis in public schools.

The CDE recently created an email address for our communities to have their voices heard regarding institutional racism. Please submit your ideas and feedback to createracialjustice@gmail.com.
text:
California Department of Education
June 15 at 3:16 PM ·

Students in the middle and high school age range are invited to attend "Student Support Circle: Institutional Racism and Implicit Bias" hosted by the CDE and State Superintendent Tony Thurmond, this Thursday, June 18 at 4 p.m, on Facebook Live. It's hosted in partnership with with National Equity Project, and will feature California Surgeon General Dr. Nadine Burke Harris.

It will also feature students from across the state speaking about what they've experienced and talk about practical solutions to institutional racism and implicit basis in public schools.

The CDE recently created an email address for our communities to have their voices heard regarding institutional racism. Please submit your ideas and feedback to createracialjustice@gmail.com.

Dear Rohnert Park High School Seniors,
We see you! You guys are facing things no other class has had deal with. We are proud of all your hard work and all you are overcoming. We want to do our small part in showing you off to our community and we are creating a tribute wall on the windows of the Sozo Student Center in University Square.
What we need from you:
1. Your favorite current picture (can be senior picture, sports picture, selfie, or anything)
2. Plans after high school
3. What have you been doing during quarantine?
4. Favorite quote
Just send the pic and info to info@sozocenter.org and we will do the rest. Congratulations to you all! So proud of you!

Please pass this on if you know any Rancho, Tech, or Credo Seniors and help us celebrate them!
#RohnertPark #rohnertparkstrong
#classof2020

post_text:
The Department of Health Services Behavioral Health Division (DHS-BHD) is very pleased to announce that the Behavioral Health Warm Line (707) 565-2652 will be available for calls starting today, April 24, 2020. We are in very uncertain times, and the warm line is a supportive resource for the community. This free and private warm line is open seven days a week from 10 a.m. to 7 p.m. The warm line has English and Spanish speaking staff answering calls and telephone interpretation for other languages.

La División de Salud Mental del Departamento de Servicios de Salud (DHS-BHD) se complace en anunciar que la Línea de Atención de Salud Mental (707) 565-2652 estará disponible para llamadas a partir de hoy, 24 de abril de 2020. Estamos en tiempos muy inciertos, y la línea cálida es un recurso de apoyo para la comunidad. Esta línea caliente gratuita y privada está abierta los siete días de la semana de 10 a.m. a 7 p.m. La línea cálida cuenta con personal que habla inglés y español para responder llamadas e interpretación telefónica para otros idiomas.

The #CALeg is working with California Governor Newsom to ensure that public agencies have all the resources they need to combat the emerging threat of the novel coronavirus.

Stay informed: http://bit.ly/3a6jMCu

-Wash hands with soap and water for at least 20 seconds.
-Clean your hands often with an alcohol-based hand sanitizer that contains at least 60% alcohol.
-Avoid touching eyes, nose or mouth with unwashed hands.
-Cover your nose and mouth with a tissue when coughing or sneezing (or an elbow or shoulder if no tissue is available).
-Discard tissue and wash your hands.
-Avoid close contact with people who are sick.
-Stay home and do not come to work if you are sick with respiratory symptoms like fever and cough.

post_text:
CRPUSD is in the process of shifting how the Board of Trustees is elected. Currently all 5 trustees are elected through an "at-large" election, meaning all residents within the District boundaries can vote for any candidate.

The District will soon adopt 5 unique and distinct Trustee Areas. There are 3 proposed Trustee Area maps. Once approved, Trustee candidates must live in a designated trustee area and will be elected by those registered voters in that reside in that particular trustee area.

There are 3 map scenarios being considered. Scenarios A, B, and C are below.

The Board is seeking community feedback as to which scenario should be adopted. Feedback can be sent to trusteeareaelections@crpusd.org. You can also share your Public Comment at an upcoming School Board meeting;
February 27, 2020 and/or March 10, 2020. These meetings are held at 7165 Burton Avenue, RP at 6:00 PM
